2","1619":"1619","1649":"1649","1637":"1637","1603":"1603","Tiverton, Devon, England":"Tiverton, Devon, England","Biddenden, Kent, England":"Biddenden, Kent, England","Ireland":"Ireland","Kittery, York County, Maine":"Kittery, York, Maine, United States","Wittersham, Kent, England":"Wittersham, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Conley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Down, Antrim, and Louth): shortened form of   Connolly  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Connley","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Conley  ."]},{"name":"Conlee","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Conley  ."]},{"name":"Coonley","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scottish Matha.","Irish: variant of   Conley  ."]},{"name":"Connolly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen, Bridie, Seamus, Aidan, Dermot, Eamon, Patrick Joseph, Colm, Cormac, Declan, Eoin.","Irish and Manx: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Conghaile</b> ‘descendant of <i>Conghal</i>’, a name meaning ‘hound valiant’, or of <b>Ó Conghalaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Conghalach</i>’, a derivative of <i>Conghal</i>; the two surnames have long been confused. Anglicized Irish forms Conneely, Connealy, Cunneely have arisen where loss of <i>gh</i> has caused lengthening of the second syllable of <i>Conghal</i>: they often also (Connacht) represent shortened forms of   McNeilly   from <i>Mac Conghaile</i>. Another possible origin is the West Cork name <b>Mac Coingheallaigh</b> (or <b>Ó Coingheallaigh</b>) ‘son (or descendant) of <i>Coingheallach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘faithful to pledges’. See   McNeilly  ."]}]},{"name":"Abraham","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the first of the Jewish patriarchs, with whom God made a covenant that his descendants should possess the land of Canaan. The Hebrew form is <i>Avraham</i>, and is of uncertain derivation. In Genesis 17:5 it is explained as ‘father of a multitude (of nations)’ (Hebrew <i>av hamon (goyim)</i>. It has always been a popular Jewish given name, and was also chosen by Christians, especially by Puritans and other fundamentalists from the 16th century onwards. Various early saints of the Eastern Roman Empire also bore this name. Its currency in the United States was greatly enhanced by the fame of  President Abraham Lincoln  (  1809–65 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Avrom","meanings":["Yiddish form of   Abraham ."]},{"name":"Avraham","meanings":["modern Hebrew form of   Abraham ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1355925,"age":30,"year":"1603","julianDay":2306544,"description":"Accession of James I. Surrender of Hugh O'Neill. Enforcement of English Law in Ireland.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":2538557,"age":49,"year":"1622","toYear":"1820","julianDay":2313484,"description":"Historical Boundaries: 1716: York, Massachusetts Bay Colony, British Colonial America 1776: York, Massachusetts, United States 1820: York, Maine, United States","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1355926,"age":68,"year":"1641","julianDay":2320424,"description":"Great Catholic-Gaelic rebellion for return of lands, later joined by Old English Catholics in Ireland. Under leadership of Irish chieftain, Rory O'More, conspiracy was formed to seize Dublin and expel the English. English settlers were driven out of Ulster. Catholics hold 59% of land in Ireland.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1355927,"age":76,"year":"1649","julianDay":2323346,"description":"The Protestant Lord Protector of England, Oliver Cromwell, landed at Dublin. His troops killed 2,000 men. A great part of lands in Munster, Leinster and Ulster (Drogheda and Wexford) was confiscated and divided among the English soldiers.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1355928,"age":99,"year":"1672","julianDay":2331746,"description":"Over 6,000 Irish boys and women sold as slaves since England gained control of Jamaica.","ju